WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:04.730
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:20.850 --> 00:00:23.720
&gt;&gt; Hello, everyone.

00:00:23.720 --> 00:00:25.570
Thank you for joining us today.

00:00:25.570 --> 00:00:28.380
My name is Betsy Peterson
and I'm the Director

00:00:28.380 --> 00:00:32.270
of the American Folklife Center
here at the Library of Congress.

00:00:32.270 --> 00:00:35.860
And, on behalf of all the
staff and the library,

00:00:35.860 --> 00:00:37.380
I want to welcome you.

00:00:37.380 --> 00:00:40.110
We're very excited
about today's event

00:00:40.110 --> 00:00:43.030
and very excited to
have you with us.

00:00:43.030 --> 00:00:46.670
And, before we move
along, I just wanted

00:00:46.670 --> 00:00:50.350
to tell you a little bit about
the American Folklife Center

00:00:50.350 --> 00:00:55.680
for those of you who don't know
that much about what we do.

00:00:55.680 --> 00:00:58.380
We are a center here
in the library,

00:00:58.380 --> 00:01:00.590
in fact in this very building.

00:01:00.590 --> 00:01:06.220
We were founded in 1976 by
Congress with the mandate

00:01:06.220 --> 00:01:11.440
to preserve and present the rich
diversity of American Folklife

00:01:11.440 --> 00:01:16.080
and we have strived hard for the
last 41 years to do just that.

00:01:16.080 --> 00:01:21.220
Now, Congress selected the
library itself as the site

00:01:21.220 --> 00:01:25.730
for the center in part because
the library already had a pretty

00:01:25.730 --> 00:01:29.150
significant archive of
traditional music and culture,

00:01:29.150 --> 00:01:32.970
which had in fact been
established in 1928.

00:01:32.970 --> 00:01:37.450
So, it was already pretty darn
big by the time we started

00:01:37.450 --> 00:01:42.870
and it has only grown in
magnitude in the last 40 years.

00:01:42.870 --> 00:01:47.990
We now have over six
million items of recordings

00:01:47.990 --> 00:01:50.870
of traditional culture,
traditional music,

00:01:50.870 --> 00:01:55.130
stories from over a hundred 140
countries throughout the world

00:01:55.130 --> 00:01:57.540
and I certainly I want
to invite you to come

00:01:57.540 --> 00:01:58.840
and listen to some of it.

00:01:58.840 --> 00:02:03.400
But, the other reason that I
think they selected the Library

00:02:03.400 --> 00:02:06.710
of Congress is because it
is, it's America's library

00:02:06.710 --> 00:02:13.000
and it has a strong commitment
to preserving the rich diversity

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:16.610
of voices in the United States
and indeed throughout the world.

00:02:16.610 --> 00:02:20.690
And, I think this even today is
very much about that commitment.

00:02:20.690 --> 00:02:26.900
So, one of the ways in which we
continue to grow our archives

00:02:26.900 --> 00:02:31.500
in - in the last few decades is
certainly through partnerships

00:02:31.500 --> 00:02:34.970
and partnerships with other
organizations, other individuals

00:02:34.970 --> 00:02:38.720
and I think today's event is
very much about that as well.

00:02:38.720 --> 00:02:43.410
And, I do want to thank our
partners for this event today.

00:02:43.410 --> 00:02:46.340
The Muslim American
Leadership Alliance.

00:02:46.340 --> 00:02:48.080
Thank you very much.

00:02:48.080 --> 00:02:50.530
And, thank you very
much to Zainab Khan.

00:02:50.530 --> 00:02:53.180
I don't know where Zainab
- ah, you're right there.

00:02:53.180 --> 00:02:54.480
Right in front of me.

00:02:54.480 --> 00:02:56.090
And, Naeem Uddin
[assumed spelling].

00:02:56.090 --> 00:02:58.270
I do - I don't know
if Naeem is here.

00:02:58.270 --> 00:02:59.910
Oh, welcome.

00:02:59.910 --> 00:03:04.710
I - I gather you came all
the way from New Orleans, so.

00:03:04.710 --> 00:03:06.380
Welcome. And, I also would

00:03:06.380 --> 00:03:10.670
like to acknowledge Mohammed
Aziz [assumed spelling],

00:03:10.670 --> 00:03:12.140
who I hope is here.

00:03:12.140 --> 00:03:15.470
I believe he is one
of the board members.

00:03:15.470 --> 00:03:19.310
Ah, okay. Welcome and thank you.

00:03:19.310 --> 00:03:21.780
I also want to acknowledge
StoryCorps [assumed spelling]

00:03:21.780 --> 00:03:26.400
who is one of the other
very critical partners in -

00:03:26.400 --> 00:03:32.800
in this event today and in this
project that Zainab is going

00:03:32.800 --> 00:03:34.670
to tell us a little
bit more about.

00:03:34.670 --> 00:03:38.890
So, once again thank you to
our staff, thank you Zainab,

00:03:38.890 --> 00:03:42.170
thank you MALA, and
thank you StoryCorps

00:03:42.170 --> 00:03:45.510
and welcome once again.

00:03:45.510 --> 00:03:54.870
[ Applause ]

00:03:54.870 --> 00:03:57.880
&gt;&gt; Good afternoon, everybody
and thank you so much

00:03:57.880 --> 00:04:01.520
for taking the time out and
joining us this afternoon

00:04:01.520 --> 00:04:07.950
for what I hope is a very, very
compelling program that each

00:04:07.950 --> 00:04:10.960
of you can understand
how much heart and soul

00:04:10.960 --> 00:04:12.720
and effort was put into it.

00:04:12.720 --> 00:04:15.530
For the past two and
a half years, MALA,

00:04:15.530 --> 00:04:18.340
Muslim American Leadership
Alliance, has really,

00:04:18.340 --> 00:04:22.950
really worked hard to collect
archive and preserve the stories

00:04:22.950 --> 00:04:25.860
of diverse Muslim Americans.

00:04:25.860 --> 00:04:29.440
And, what I really noticed was

00:04:29.440 --> 00:04:30.970
that as a Muslim
American myself,

00:04:30.970 --> 00:04:33.610
I felt that my voice
didn't belong.

00:04:33.610 --> 00:04:37.590
I didn't know where
my story would belong

00:04:37.590 --> 00:04:39.990
and where my voice
would be accepted.

00:04:39.990 --> 00:04:43.720
And, hence, a group of us had
started the Muslim American

00:04:43.720 --> 00:04:46.910
Leadership Alliance
and we're very proud

00:04:46.910 --> 00:04:50.480
to showcase the narratives
on the collection

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:53.230
of stories that we have today.

00:04:53.230 --> 00:04:57.860
MALA is a 501C3 Civic and
Community Organization

00:04:57.860 --> 00:05:02.050
and we're committed to promote
individual freedom diversity

00:05:02.050 --> 00:05:04.620
and to celebrate heritage.

00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:07.320
Our core storytelling program is

00:05:07.320 --> 00:05:11.350
to amplify voices
of Muslim Americans.

00:05:11.350 --> 00:05:12.650
Really when you think about it,

00:05:12.650 --> 00:05:16.430
Muslim Americans are the most
broadest and diverse group

00:05:16.430 --> 00:05:20.040
in America, holding the
broadest range of diversity

00:05:20.040 --> 00:05:23.040
across ethnicities,
nationalities,

00:05:23.040 --> 00:05:26.820
various demographics
in this country.

00:05:26.820 --> 00:05:30.780
These stories are a prime
example of liberating new voices

00:05:30.780 --> 00:05:34.270
from behind a cloud of
stereotypes, the stereotypes

00:05:34.270 --> 00:05:36.520
that have come from
within the community,

00:05:36.520 --> 00:05:38.390
stereotypes that have
come from the media

00:05:38.390 --> 00:05:42.190
and actually providing
people a platform

00:05:42.190 --> 00:05:46.770
to share their personal
individual experiences.

00:05:46.770 --> 00:05:50.500
To date, MALA has collected,
archived and preserved

00:05:50.500 --> 00:05:56.070
over 350 stories of
Muslim Americans and many

00:05:56.070 --> 00:05:58.940
of these stories were also
archived into the Library

00:05:58.940 --> 00:06:02.430
of Congress and really through
our community partnership

00:06:02.430 --> 00:06:08.160
with StoryCorps, several were
even aired on NPR programs.

00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:10.410
And, as you listen
to these stories,

00:06:10.410 --> 00:06:13.860
you'll hear just a small
sample of what we've been able

00:06:13.860 --> 00:06:20.420
to produce that presents just
the vast diverse experiences

00:06:20.420 --> 00:06:23.610
that really make us human.

00:06:23.610 --> 00:06:28.900
These are stories of people that
hail from Kazakhstan, Albania,

00:06:28.900 --> 00:06:37.380
Algeria, Siberia even, India,
Iraq, Iran, Israel, Somalia,

00:06:37.380 --> 00:06:41.540
Mauritania, Mali,
Nigeria, Morocco, France -

00:06:41.540 --> 00:06:44.440
pretty much every country
- Palestine, Yemen,

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:46.630
Saudi Arabia, Venezuela.

00:06:46.630 --> 00:06:49.080
All of these people
hailed from these countries

00:06:49.080 --> 00:06:54.340
yet have shared their
story as Muslim Americans.

00:06:54.340 --> 00:06:57.010
And, I really hope that
these stories will continue

00:06:57.010 --> 00:06:59.810
to have an incredible
potential to harness engagement

00:06:59.810 --> 00:07:03.070
and build bridges all while
stressing the importance

00:07:03.070 --> 00:07:05.470
of inclusion and individuality.

00:07:05.470 --> 00:07:09.350
I want to thank the
American Folklife Center

00:07:09.350 --> 00:07:11.730
for providing us the
opportunity to hold

00:07:11.730 --> 00:07:14.130
such a significant event.

00:07:14.130 --> 00:07:17.310
I want to thank StoryCorps
for over two and a half years

00:07:17.310 --> 00:07:19.360
of partnership as
we continue to grow

00:07:19.360 --> 00:07:23.730
and record stories all
throughout America.

00:07:23.730 --> 00:07:26.460
And, I want to thank the
Library of Congress also

00:07:26.460 --> 00:07:31.030
for providing us this incredible
opportunity for generations

00:07:31.030 --> 00:07:36.070
to come to come back and listen
to these stories and have pride

00:07:36.070 --> 00:07:39.270
in the personal experiences,
whether they are triumphs,

00:07:39.270 --> 00:07:43.240
adversities, struggles,
they are human journeys

00:07:43.240 --> 00:07:46.010
and they ought to be recognized.

00:07:46.010 --> 00:07:49.600
We will now play a
sample compilation of some

00:07:49.600 --> 00:07:52.650
of the stories that have
been produced and even aired

00:07:52.650 --> 00:07:55.940
in partnership with
StoryCorps and NPR.

