00:14:42.990 --> 00:14:44.290
&gt;&gt; Hi everyone.

00:14:44.290 --> 00:14:46.060
Thanks for coming.

00:14:46.060 --> 00:14:49.950
Before I start, I did
my story with MALA

00:14:49.950 --> 00:14:53.040
and I was very thrilled with
what MALA is doing and all

00:14:53.040 --> 00:14:56.430
of these stories and diversity
of American - Muslims in America

00:14:56.430 --> 00:15:00.480
and - and also the
communities they live in.

00:15:00.480 --> 00:15:05.930
I came to U.S. - I was born in
Kabul - in Kabul, Afghanistan.

00:15:05.930 --> 00:15:09.290
I spent my early
teen years in Kabul.

00:15:09.290 --> 00:15:13.160
I was living there during
the entire Taliban period

00:15:13.160 --> 00:15:17.160
and then I moved to U.S.
when I was in eleventh grade

00:15:17.160 --> 00:15:21.840
through a State Department
funded exchange student program.

00:15:21.840 --> 00:15:24.900
And, the way the exchange
student program worked was

00:15:24.900 --> 00:15:26.790
that the students would
be placed randomly

00:15:26.790 --> 00:15:29.390
across the U.S. anywhere.

00:15:29.390 --> 00:15:33.240
And, I was placed
in Berne, Indiana

00:15:33.240 --> 00:15:36.380
and I don't think you can
even find Berne on a map.

00:15:36.380 --> 00:15:37.730
I came from Kabul.

00:15:37.730 --> 00:15:40.270
Kabul has a five
million population.

00:15:40.270 --> 00:15:44.150
Berne had five thousand
- the entire town.

00:15:44.150 --> 00:15:46.770
My high school in Kabul
had ten thousand students.

00:15:46.770 --> 00:15:48.070
Berne had five hundred.

00:15:48.070 --> 00:15:50.850
I don't think they had
ever seen a brown person,

00:15:50.850 --> 00:15:52.990
let alone a person
from Afghanistan.

00:15:52.990 --> 00:15:56.660
So, it was an unbelievably
amazing experience living

00:15:56.660 --> 00:16:02.220
with this family that took me
in and became my legal guardians

00:16:02.220 --> 00:16:06.650
after that exchange
student year ended.

00:16:06.650 --> 00:16:11.630
And, Berne, Indiana is not like
Washington, DC or New York City.

00:16:11.630 --> 00:16:15.290
It is a very conservative,
majority white,

00:16:15.290 --> 00:16:18.410
I would say Republican town.

00:16:18.410 --> 00:16:22.340
So, combine all those, you
already have certain perception

00:16:22.340 --> 00:16:24.470
of what that community
would look like.

00:16:24.470 --> 00:16:29.040
But, to me it was my family
there and the were [inaudible]

00:16:29.040 --> 00:16:32.820
and the way I became such
a really important part

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:35.870
of that community really changed
my perception of what America -

00:16:35.870 --> 00:16:38.330
what small town America
is all about.

00:16:38.330 --> 00:16:42.550
So, one of the reasons I wanted
to share my story was because of

00:16:42.550 --> 00:16:46.410
that family and friends I
found in - in a part of America

00:16:46.410 --> 00:16:49.590
where you always hear about
racism, you always hear

00:16:49.590 --> 00:16:54.750
about bigotry, but to me,
I made friends with one

00:16:54.750 --> 00:16:58.370
of my friend's grandpar
- grandad who I went

00:16:58.370 --> 00:17:00.470
to their house and
played cornhole with.

00:17:00.470 --> 00:17:03.050
I don't know if you
know what cornhole is -

00:17:03.050 --> 00:17:05.870
if you're from midwest
- Mideast U.S.,

00:17:05.870 --> 00:17:07.510
you will know what cornhole is.

00:17:07.510 --> 00:17:09.550
And, I drank moonshine
with them.

00:17:09.550 --> 00:17:10.850
[Laughter].

00:17:10.850 --> 00:17:12.980
And, I wasn't - I was under
age, so just forget about that.

00:17:12.980 --> 00:17:15.720
But, he was a Vietnam veteran.

00:17:15.720 --> 00:17:18.560
So, when I told him I was
from Afghanistan and he was

00:17:18.560 --> 00:17:22.000
like so welcoming and - and
then we sat, we - we, you know,

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:23.900
we had - they had
a whole barbeque,

00:17:23.900 --> 00:17:27.870
but that's what made me want
to share my story is that a kid

00:17:27.870 --> 00:17:30.870
like 16, 15, when
I was in undergrad,

00:17:30.870 --> 00:17:33.890
then I spent time in Ohio.

00:17:33.890 --> 00:17:37.930
Very young kid from Afghanistan
in the middle of nowhere

00:17:37.930 --> 00:17:41.500
in America making friends
with the most unlikely people.

00:17:41.500 --> 00:17:42.800
And, they welcomed me.

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:44.100
All of them.

00:17:44.100 --> 00:17:47.280
I mean, of course, there's
certain racism that you feel,

00:17:47.280 --> 00:17:50.560
but for the most part, it was
an amazing experience and one

00:17:50.560 --> 00:17:52.580
of the reasons I wanted
to, you know, share.

00:17:52.580 --> 00:17:55.580
&gt;&gt; I think that's an incredible
story, Zabi, and, you know,

00:17:55.580 --> 00:17:58.260
I think what you - what you
also mentioned is very important

00:17:58.260 --> 00:18:00.920
because dispelling stereotypes,

00:18:00.920 --> 00:18:03.540
I think your story
in itself does that.

00:18:03.540 --> 00:18:07.730
It goes against the grievance
narrative and it actually shows

00:18:07.730 --> 00:18:12.120
that you were welcomed, you were
able to create a new identity

00:18:12.120 --> 00:18:15.870
and an American identity and you
were welcomed and you obviously

00:18:15.870 --> 00:18:17.800
as a human you experienced
things,

00:18:17.800 --> 00:18:19.880
but it's - it's a success.

00:18:19.880 --> 00:18:21.180
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Yeah.

00:18:21.180 --> 00:18:24.930
And, it - I think maybe
a little different

00:18:24.930 --> 00:18:27.220
because I was a student.

00:18:27.220 --> 00:18:30.430
So, I was in university,
living on campus in a dorm room

00:18:30.430 --> 00:18:33.800
and all freshman kids, this
was a new experience for them.

00:18:33.800 --> 00:18:36.850
So, everybody coming to
live in a campus dorm room,

00:18:36.850 --> 00:18:38.150
they're all away from home.

00:18:38.150 --> 00:18:40.480
I was away from home, so all of
those kids were away from home.

00:18:40.480 --> 00:18:43.960
And, we all had that one shared
experience of being students

00:18:43.960 --> 00:18:45.370
in a small, you know, campus.

00:18:45.370 --> 00:18:48.680
That's - I would say that was
an opportunity and an advantage

00:18:48.680 --> 00:18:50.970
for me to be able to make all
these friends and, you know,

00:18:50.970 --> 00:18:52.650
with different communities.

00:18:52.650 --> 00:18:53.950
&gt;&gt; That's great.

00:18:53.950 --> 00:18:58.520
Yeah. Supna, you had also shared
a very compelling story with -

00:18:58.520 --> 00:19:03.210
with MALA as a, you know, Muslim
American with your heritage

00:19:03.210 --> 00:19:06.670
and your, you know, very unique
story of where you come from

00:19:06.670 --> 00:19:07.970
and your parent's story.

00:19:07.970 --> 00:19:10.290
So, if you could share that
with us that would be wonderful.

00:19:10.290 --> 00:19:12.100
&gt;&gt; Hi everyone.

00:19:12.100 --> 00:19:13.490
Thanks for coming today.

00:19:13.490 --> 00:19:16.580
So, the profile I wrote focused

00:19:16.580 --> 00:19:21.190
on I guess two stages
of my life.

00:19:21.190 --> 00:19:24.260
Me through my parents and their
experiences having left Pakistan

00:19:24.260 --> 00:19:30.370
in 1981 and the context in which
they left and then me growing

00:19:30.370 --> 00:19:33.350
up through the 80s and 90s
and getting married about,

00:19:33.350 --> 00:19:34.970
you know, four years ago.

00:19:34.970 --> 00:19:37.790
And, for me - I'll get
into the details of those,

00:19:37.790 --> 00:19:41.130
but the one common thread
that I realized in writing

00:19:41.130 --> 00:19:46.740
that which was most compelling,
especially in the context of,

00:19:46.740 --> 00:19:49.730
you know, for millennials,
especially growing up post 911

00:19:49.730 --> 00:19:51.600
and being any minority,
not even just Muslim,

00:19:51.600 --> 00:19:54.190
is that there's always
adversity,

00:19:54.190 --> 00:19:56.840
there's always experiences
that we go

00:19:56.840 --> 00:20:00.020
through regardless whether
there's economic adversity

00:20:00.020 --> 00:20:03.050
or something having to do with
the disability or any kind

00:20:03.050 --> 00:20:06.120
of disadvantage that we
experience that makes us

00:20:06.120 --> 00:20:09.510
in the moment feel like we're
going through something worse

00:20:09.510 --> 00:20:12.380
than others, but in
hindsight when you look back,

00:20:12.380 --> 00:20:13.930
it's a learning experience.

00:20:13.930 --> 00:20:15.310
You grow from it.

00:20:15.310 --> 00:20:17.290
You're a better person
through it.

00:20:17.290 --> 00:20:22.330
And, the politics of today
make things feel more sensitive

00:20:22.330 --> 00:20:27.670
and worse or makes us feel
that we're in a situation

00:20:27.670 --> 00:20:31.820
that can't be overcome, but
when you look at the experiences

00:20:31.820 --> 00:20:34.240
of everyone around you
that, you know, precede more

00:20:34.240 --> 00:20:37.650
than one generation, like
my parents coming to America

00:20:37.650 --> 00:20:39.360
or anyone in this audience
whether it was their

00:20:39.360 --> 00:20:41.650
grandparents or great,
great grandparents that came

00:20:41.650 --> 00:20:43.810
to the U.S. from somewhere else.

00:20:43.810 --> 00:20:45.790
We've all been through -

00:20:45.790 --> 00:20:48.470
we as in our family histories
have been through periods

00:20:48.470 --> 00:20:52.700
where we had to figure out who
we were, what our identity means

00:20:52.700 --> 00:20:55.550
to us and how we
can integrate it

00:20:55.550 --> 00:20:58.290
to all being American
at the same time.

00:20:58.290 --> 00:21:02.900
And, I think that's something
that for me means everything now

00:21:02.900 --> 00:21:05.060
in our political environment
when I look at my nephews

00:21:05.060 --> 00:21:08.240
and nieces who aren't even 10
yet of what I'm going to share

00:21:08.240 --> 00:21:12.100
with them about what it means to
grow up American and be Muslim

00:21:12.100 --> 00:21:15.170
or Pakistani or anything
other hyphen that you want to,

00:21:15.170 --> 00:21:17.440
you know, put in
there for yourself.

00:21:17.440 --> 00:21:22.320
And, with my parents,
they left Pakistan in 1981

00:21:22.320 --> 00:21:26.250
as the country was being
[inaudible] during the cold war

00:21:26.250 --> 00:21:29.980
under the dictatorship of
Prime Minister [inaudible].

00:21:29.980 --> 00:21:35.060
My dad was a liberal who was
part of Pakistan Television.

00:21:35.060 --> 00:21:38.030
His dream was just to be like
a filmmaker, write soap operas,

00:21:38.030 --> 00:21:39.840
[inaudible], dramas
and just, you know,

00:21:39.840 --> 00:21:41.770
his friends were
writers and musicians

00:21:41.770 --> 00:21:44.200
and he was a very jovial person.

00:21:44.200 --> 00:21:48.150
And, with increasing religious
[inaudible] that was coming

00:21:48.150 --> 00:21:49.450
into the public's fear

00:21:49.450 --> 00:21:52.670
of Pakistani society
[inaudible] became a factor

00:21:52.670 --> 00:21:54.010
of your employment.

00:21:54.010 --> 00:21:58.870
And, because my dad didn't fit
into the expectations of the -

00:21:58.870 --> 00:22:02.870
the government and a certain
increasingly orthodox society

00:22:02.870 --> 00:22:05.560
was expecting of him, he
basically got demoted.

00:22:05.560 --> 00:22:08.460
I was born in a city called
Karachi, which was - is -

00:22:08.460 --> 00:22:12.430
continues to be pretty
cosmopolitan like New York City.

00:22:12.430 --> 00:22:15.370
My dad was general manager
of Pakistan Television.

00:22:15.370 --> 00:22:18.230
He got demoted [inaudible],
no offense,

00:22:18.230 --> 00:22:22.140
but [inaudible] was not
exactly where he wanted to end

00:22:22.140 --> 00:22:25.030
up if you were in the
television industry.

00:22:25.030 --> 00:22:29.560
And, because my family didn't
come from a wealthy background,

00:22:29.560 --> 00:22:31.610
we were lucky enough
to be able to immigrate

00:22:31.610 --> 00:22:34.440
to the United States where
my father had a sister

00:22:34.440 --> 00:22:35.740
who had already settled here.

00:22:35.740 --> 00:22:37.520
My parents started over.

00:22:37.520 --> 00:22:41.130
My mother was a painter and with
my father's background in film,

00:22:41.130 --> 00:22:44.880
there was really no
translatable, successful career

00:22:44.880 --> 00:22:47.430
to start over again
in the United States.

00:22:47.430 --> 00:22:48.750
They had a little apartment

00:22:48.750 --> 00:22:51.970
and my parents first
jobs were fast food.

00:22:51.970 --> 00:22:55.220
And, especially I think for
a person like my father,

00:22:55.220 --> 00:23:00.940
that has to hurt personally in
terms of who you think you are,

00:23:00.940 --> 00:23:02.240
what you've achieved in life

00:23:02.240 --> 00:23:04.670
and where you're
starting over at 40.

00:23:04.670 --> 00:23:05.970
I'm 40 now myself.

00:23:05.970 --> 00:23:07.270
My father has passed away.

00:23:07.270 --> 00:23:10.170
It's been ten years and I
can look back at my childhood

00:23:10.170 --> 00:23:13.610
and look at all kinds of
different experiences we had

00:23:13.610 --> 00:23:18.130
that were difficult, but I think
I always just attributed it

00:23:18.130 --> 00:23:20.310
to being an immigrant.

00:23:20.310 --> 00:23:22.680
That first generation,
understanding

00:23:22.680 --> 00:23:24.480
that people aren't going

00:23:24.480 --> 00:23:27.440
to get certain things
and yeah it sucks.

00:23:27.440 --> 00:23:30.400
You know, sometimes you
don't have enough money

00:23:30.400 --> 00:23:33.610
to do the things your
girl friends are doing

00:23:33.610 --> 00:23:34.910
in sixth grade.

00:23:34.910 --> 00:23:36.210
You're not going to get
to go to the slumber party

00:23:36.210 --> 00:23:37.600
because your parents don't
understand the culture

00:23:37.600 --> 00:23:39.960
and they're afraid of all kinds
of bad things happening to you

00:23:39.960 --> 00:23:42.600
because they have a lot of
time to make up a lot of stuff

00:23:42.600 --> 00:23:45.910
and watch the 4:00 news and
they think that's all American

00:23:45.910 --> 00:23:47.210
society is.

00:23:47.210 --> 00:23:51.810
But, you know, we fight, we push
for boundaries, we - we learn

00:23:51.810 --> 00:23:54.580
and ask for more
responsibilities to figure

00:23:54.580 --> 00:23:59.090
out our own space and we
figure out what all the labels

00:23:59.090 --> 00:24:02.250
that are being put on
us actually mean to us.

00:24:02.250 --> 00:24:04.900
For myself, my family
is [inaudible],

00:24:04.900 --> 00:24:07.070
which is a minority
- religious minority

00:24:07.070 --> 00:24:09.710
in Pakistan - Muslim
minority even.

00:24:09.710 --> 00:24:11.470
So, growing up in
Southern California,

00:24:11.470 --> 00:24:14.140
I couldn't even just say I was
Muslim, because among Muslims,

00:24:14.140 --> 00:24:15.950
I was a different thing.

00:24:15.950 --> 00:24:18.510
So, I never really
fit in anywhere

00:24:18.510 --> 00:24:21.950
and it took me a long
time to be okay with that.

00:24:21.950 --> 00:24:24.210
And - and, all the friends
I made by the time I was

00:24:24.210 --> 00:24:27.340
in college happened
to be - to be blunt,

00:24:27.340 --> 00:24:29.440
middle class white
girls who grew

00:24:29.440 --> 00:24:31.270
up in conservative
families like me.

00:24:31.270 --> 00:24:33.770
What we had in common were
the simple joys of life.

00:24:33.770 --> 00:24:35.590
We were going to the
movies at 10:00 at night

00:24:35.590 --> 00:24:38.180
and our parents weren't
there to get mad at us.

00:24:38.180 --> 00:24:41.180
It really had nothing to do
with a specific religion.

00:24:41.180 --> 00:24:44.220
And, our values were the same.

00:24:44.220 --> 00:24:45.980
We were studying, we were
trying to go to law school

00:24:45.980 --> 00:24:50.280
or med school or whatever and
our friendships were based

00:24:50.280 --> 00:24:53.480
on our trusts that we had
in each - in each other,

00:24:53.480 --> 00:24:57.300
the respect we had for each
other and just being girls.

00:24:57.300 --> 00:24:59.100
But, the exposure we also had

00:24:59.100 --> 00:25:01.830
to each other's families
allows us to learn.

00:25:01.830 --> 00:25:06.480
My best friends were Catholic
or Jewish or Hindu or Vietnamese

00:25:06.480 --> 00:25:08.520
and Buddhist and
they came to my house

00:25:08.520 --> 00:25:11.720
and it was a Muslim household
and they were exposed

00:25:11.720 --> 00:25:15.410
to Pakistani food, south Asian
clothing, Bollywood music

00:25:15.410 --> 00:25:17.260
on the radio if my
dad was playing it

00:25:17.260 --> 00:25:19.140
and it was [inaudible]
of experiences.

00:25:19.140 --> 00:25:23.050
It wasn't just being Muslin,
because Muslin doesn't -

00:25:23.050 --> 00:25:25.800
it has no one singular
definition.

00:25:25.800 --> 00:25:30.040
And, if you fast forward
today when I look at my nephew

00:25:30.040 --> 00:25:34.620
and niece who are 9 and 7,
they're growing up in Indiana.

00:25:34.620 --> 00:25:36.400
They're, I think, the
only Pakistani kids

00:25:36.400 --> 00:25:38.070
in their neighborhood.

00:25:38.070 --> 00:25:40.480
My husband's Catholic
from Richmond

00:25:40.480 --> 00:25:44.170
and their favorite visit to
Virginia is for Christmas.

00:25:44.170 --> 00:25:47.750
And, I love the fact
that they have exposure

00:25:47.750 --> 00:25:52.780
to different faiths and
not different cultures,

00:25:52.780 --> 00:25:54.370
because they're 100%
even more American

00:25:54.370 --> 00:25:55.990
than me, they were born here.

00:25:55.990 --> 00:25:57.600
And, for them, they
don't flinch.

00:25:57.600 --> 00:26:01.020
They easily move fluidly from
wearing Pakistani clothes

00:26:01.020 --> 00:26:05.960
on Saturday because they're
going to some baby's baptism,

00:26:05.960 --> 00:26:08.220
which we call [inaudible],
or then, you know,

00:26:08.220 --> 00:26:11.750
going to a Christmas
party the following week

00:26:11.750 --> 00:26:17.470
because it's December 20
something and it's the season.

00:26:17.470 --> 00:26:23.370
And, to me it's that fluidity
that makes America great.

00:26:23.370 --> 00:26:26.870
It's that respect and
balance that the public

00:26:26.870 --> 00:26:29.870
and the community irrespective
of politics and irrespective

00:26:29.870 --> 00:26:32.750
of whatever particular
moment we're in.

00:26:32.750 --> 00:26:36.420
That as sense is being American
is not going to go away in mind

00:26:36.420 --> 00:26:42.450
and it lets me be Pakistani,
American and any other thing

00:26:42.450 --> 00:26:44.550
that I listed in my profile

00:26:44.550 --> 00:26:49.150
and that why I couldn't
ever live anywhere else.

00:26:49.150 --> 00:26:50.450
&gt;&gt; Thank you, Supna.

00:26:50.450 --> 00:26:51.750
That was very, very well said.

00:26:51.750 --> 00:26:53.370
Thank you.

00:26:53.370 --> 00:27:00.090
Ahmed, you have also had
a very compelling journey

00:27:00.090 --> 00:27:02.810
in achieving the American
dream and I'd love for you

00:27:02.810 --> 00:27:07.150
to share a little bit about
your own personal experience,

00:27:07.150 --> 00:27:09.230
what you shared with MALA.

00:27:09.230 --> 00:27:11.490
&gt;&gt; I'm terrible with
technology and it continues.

00:27:11.490 --> 00:27:14.010
First of all, thank you.

00:27:14.010 --> 00:27:17.050
So, like everyone else,
I am an immigrant.

00:27:17.050 --> 00:27:18.350
I from Pakistan.

00:27:18.350 --> 00:27:21.090
Actually, immigrated here when
I was 2 and my parents came,

00:27:21.090 --> 00:27:22.720
you know, same message,
American dream.

00:27:22.720 --> 00:27:24.620
And, you know, I thought
it was important to talk

00:27:24.620 --> 00:27:26.010
about the American dream.

00:27:26.010 --> 00:27:29.100
I don't think people really -
they don't really give gratitude

00:27:29.100 --> 00:27:30.840
to the idea of the
American dream.

00:27:30.840 --> 00:27:33.950
You know, I'm now 33 and, you
know, my entire life I grew

00:27:33.950 --> 00:27:35.610
up saying, you know, I immigrate

00:27:35.610 --> 00:27:38.420
and not really understanding
what my parents gave up and,

00:27:38.420 --> 00:27:40.740
you know, what they had to
go through and what we went

00:27:40.740 --> 00:27:42.800
through really to assimilate.

00:27:42.800 --> 00:27:44.820
So, I came here at
2 and my parents,

00:27:44.820 --> 00:27:46.120
you know, changed careers.

00:27:46.120 --> 00:27:47.710
My dad was in the
Army back in Pakistan.

00:27:47.710 --> 00:27:49.280
My mom was a housewife.

00:27:49.280 --> 00:27:50.670
My dad opened up shop.

00:27:50.670 --> 00:27:53.010
He was hit hard with
the recession

00:27:53.010 --> 00:27:54.550
like a lot of other people.

00:27:54.550 --> 00:27:57.320
He lost his house or our
house, he lost his business.

00:27:57.320 --> 00:28:00.240
I actually got into law school
at the same time that happened.

00:28:00.240 --> 00:28:01.540
Not once did they flinch.

00:28:01.540 --> 00:28:04.180
Not once did they complain
about being in this country.

00:28:04.180 --> 00:28:06.940
They figured a way
to get me my loans.

00:28:06.940 --> 00:28:10.030
They figured a way to make sure
I was able to attend law school.

00:28:10.030 --> 00:28:13.680
I worked. My - I liked to
- I like to brag, you know.

00:28:13.680 --> 00:28:17.660
You always hear parents say I
had to walk 20 miles in snow to,

00:28:17.660 --> 00:28:18.960
you know, get to school.

00:28:18.960 --> 00:28:21.060
My third year of law school, I
went to school out in Michigan.

00:28:21.060 --> 00:28:22.740
I - I lived in Chicago.

00:28:22.740 --> 00:28:25.650
I scheduled all my classes for
Thursday afternoon and Friday,

00:28:25.650 --> 00:28:27.910
so I used to drive
up Thursday morning,

00:28:27.910 --> 00:28:29.980
sleep on my friend's
couch Thursday night

00:28:29.980 --> 00:28:32.040
and drive back Friday
night to avoid paying rent

00:28:32.040 --> 00:28:35.920
and I would just buy him dinner
and I worked a sunglasses kiosk

00:28:35.920 --> 00:28:37.890
on the weekends and
during the week.

00:28:37.890 --> 00:28:39.650
So, about 40 hours a week.

00:28:39.650 --> 00:28:41.580
So, I can't wait to
tell my kids that story,

00:28:41.580 --> 00:28:42.880
because I legitimately
am going to hold

00:28:42.880 --> 00:28:44.180
that over them [laughter].

00:28:44.180 --> 00:28:45.480
But, that's the idea, right?

00:28:45.480 --> 00:28:46.780
That's the American dream.

00:28:46.780 --> 00:28:49.650
My parents, you know, I saw
that work ethic growing up

00:28:49.650 --> 00:28:51.760
and I was able to replicate it.

00:28:51.760 --> 00:28:53.060
You know, and that
actually lead me

00:28:53.060 --> 00:28:55.060
to my basically currently
professional life.

00:28:55.060 --> 00:28:57.730
I, you know, I do compliance
law for a health system

00:28:57.730 --> 00:29:00.500
in Chicago and, you know, it
lead me to my current decision,

00:29:00.500 --> 00:29:02.100
which, you know, I won't
go into detail here,

00:29:02.100 --> 00:29:03.760
but I decided to run for office.

00:29:03.760 --> 00:29:06.230
And, you know, running
for office right now is -

00:29:06.230 --> 00:29:08.800
is basically like the pinnacle
of an immigrant's dream,

00:29:08.800 --> 00:29:11.580
like seeing your child being
able to run for office.

00:29:11.580 --> 00:29:14.780
And, you know, truth be
told, after I decided to run

00:29:14.780 --> 00:29:19.370
for office, my dad, 67, was
let go from his job because he,

00:29:19.370 --> 00:29:23.190
you know, wasn't technical
savvy enough to keep

00:29:23.190 --> 00:29:25.390
up with the computer
systems at work.

00:29:25.390 --> 00:29:27.050
He didn't complain.

00:29:27.050 --> 00:29:28.350
What did he do?

00:29:28.350 --> 00:29:30.080
He literally the next day
signed up to be a Lyft driver

00:29:30.080 --> 00:29:31.750
and drives Lyft as a
67-year-old [laugher].

00:29:31.750 --> 00:29:34.040
And, that's what I mean when you
talk about the American dream

00:29:34.040 --> 00:29:38.570
and really making sure that, you
know, we appreciate it and it -

00:29:38.570 --> 00:29:41.350
it - it - we take it for granite
for the idea that we hear it

00:29:41.350 --> 00:29:44.210
so often but, you know,
there are people who believe

00:29:44.210 --> 00:29:46.480
in the American dream so much
that stuff like that happens

00:29:46.480 --> 00:29:47.780
and they just keep
rolling with it.

00:29:47.780 --> 00:29:50.790
And, you know, they see their
kids and I'll see my kids based

00:29:50.790 --> 00:29:52.670
on the fruits of my parent's
labors and, you know,

00:29:52.670 --> 00:29:55.730
it's something I really
think is important to share.

00:29:55.730 --> 00:29:57.030
&gt;&gt; Thank you Ahmed.

00:29:57.030 --> 00:29:59.760
That's - that's a very - that's
a - that's actually something

00:29:59.760 --> 00:30:01.850
that I think resonates
quite frankly with a lot

00:30:01.850 --> 00:30:03.900
of us sitting in this room.

00:30:03.900 --> 00:30:06.740
Especially coming as
a, you know, from a -

00:30:06.740 --> 00:30:10.400
a child as an immigrant, the
sacrifices that people have made

00:30:10.400 --> 00:30:14.070
to make sure that your
life here is what it is.

00:30:14.070 --> 00:30:18.270
You know, I know myself, my
own father escaped oppression

00:30:18.270 --> 00:30:21.420
and subjugation in its
worst form from Afghanistan

00:30:21.420 --> 00:30:24.980
and came here and
rebuilt his entire life

00:30:24.980 --> 00:30:27.230
and his identity here and
I know what he sacrificed

00:30:27.230 --> 00:30:29.460
and what he had gone
through to ensure that myself

00:30:29.460 --> 00:30:33.290
and my sisters have the
life that we have now.

00:30:33.290 --> 00:30:36.470
I'm going to open the floor
to the audience for Q&amp;A.

00:30:36.470 --> 00:30:39.080
you know, please take
advantage of the panelist

00:30:39.080 --> 00:30:42.920
that we have here and also any
questions that you may have

00:30:42.920 --> 00:30:45.280
in regards to the
storytelling process.

00:30:45.280 --> 00:30:48.100
You're more than welcomed
to go on our website,

00:30:48.100 --> 00:30:51.650
which is www.malanational.org.

00:30:51.650 --> 00:30:53.120
You can share your story.

00:30:53.120 --> 00:30:54.510
You can read the stories.

00:30:54.510 --> 00:30:56.620
You can listen to the stories.

00:30:56.620 --> 00:30:59.080
And, you know, the
floor is open.

00:30:59.080 --> 00:31:04.030
And, Thea [assumed spelling] is
walking around with a microphone

00:31:04.030 --> 00:31:06.970
in case anybody has a question.

00:31:11.290 --> 00:31:16.910
None? Somebody has
to have one question.

00:31:16.910 --> 00:31:20.840
&gt;&gt; Hello. I am also from
Pakistan, so I can pretty relate

00:31:20.840 --> 00:31:23.710
with the two persons
here, Supna and Ahmed.

00:31:23.710 --> 00:31:27.370
And, as my projecting, I
believe from results based

00:31:27.370 --> 00:31:32.050
on assimilation of Pakistani
community in the United States.

00:31:32.050 --> 00:31:35.690
And, I have one question
from Supna.

00:31:35.690 --> 00:31:41.170
As you just mentioned that you
married to a Catholic and how -

00:31:41.170 --> 00:31:46.550
how the Pakistani community and
the families perceive such kind

00:31:46.550 --> 00:31:50.110
of marriages in which, you
know, there is a huge difference

00:31:50.110 --> 00:31:55.210
of religion and the
nationality and ethnicity

00:31:55.210 --> 00:31:57.020
and there is a difference.

00:31:57.020 --> 00:31:58.820
So, do you think
that all families

00:31:58.820 --> 00:32:01.080
across the board accepts
that and if they don't,

00:32:01.080 --> 00:32:05.430
which communities do
not accept it as such?

00:32:06.920 --> 00:32:08.960
&gt;&gt; Thanks for your question.

00:32:08.960 --> 00:32:12.260
Well, interfaith marriages
are a new experience

00:32:12.260 --> 00:32:14.470
for first generation immigrants.

00:32:14.470 --> 00:32:17.070
I mean, every Pakistani
family isn't first generation,

00:32:17.070 --> 00:32:18.610
but predominantly they are.

00:32:18.610 --> 00:32:24.550
And, I think the insularity
that maybe is where you're going

00:32:24.550 --> 00:32:27.380
like with your question is
sometimes coming from a place

00:32:27.380 --> 00:32:31.100
from parents where they
have fears of the unknown

00:32:31.100 --> 00:32:33.980
and being immigrants that
have migrated from one place

00:32:33.980 --> 00:32:35.620
to another, it's not

00:32:35.620 --> 00:32:39.180
that they're anti whatever
the other is, but it's more

00:32:39.180 --> 00:32:40.480
of fear of preserving.

00:32:40.480 --> 00:32:42.800
Whether it's language
or culture.

00:32:42.800 --> 00:32:45.280
I remember when I was young
my father would say oh

00:32:45.280 --> 00:32:48.420
if you marry out, you know,
how will I talk to him.

00:32:48.420 --> 00:32:50.800
I'm like, you speak
English perfectly fine.

00:32:50.800 --> 00:32:56.620
But, his point was his command
of, you know, his argument,

00:32:56.620 --> 00:32:58.670
his - his emotion, his heart.

00:32:58.670 --> 00:33:00.510
That would be in [inaudible].

00:33:00.510 --> 00:33:02.130
That wouldn't be in English.

00:33:02.130 --> 00:33:05.540
And, so I - he - he's coming
from an emotional place

00:33:05.540 --> 00:33:08.240
when he said that, you know,
and I can understand that

00:33:08.240 --> 00:33:10.050
and I think that's probably
why it took me a long time

00:33:10.050 --> 00:33:12.610
to get married, because I
spent a lot of years trying

00:33:12.610 --> 00:33:16.190
to meet somebody that
- and this is the thing

00:33:16.190 --> 00:33:17.490
about identity right.

00:33:17.490 --> 00:33:19.310
Someone can fit on
paper on the outside,

00:33:19.310 --> 00:33:22.300
but that doesn't mean they
fit you on the inside.

00:33:22.300 --> 00:33:26.290
Because I - I like everyone else
here, our experiences are unique

00:33:26.290 --> 00:33:28.320
to us and they're
like in our heads.

00:33:28.320 --> 00:33:29.860
They're not external.

00:33:29.860 --> 00:33:31.270
And, you know the funniest
thing I can you tell you

00:33:31.270 --> 00:33:33.640
about my husband is
that on the outside,

00:33:33.640 --> 00:33:35.020
we couldn't be more different.

00:33:35.020 --> 00:33:37.580
Voted opposite at the
election, different religions,

00:33:37.580 --> 00:33:45.060
all kinds of different stuff
but, you know, no one reminds me

00:33:45.060 --> 00:33:48.520
of my family more than
him, like his habits.

00:33:48.520 --> 00:33:50.750
Like the way he says and
does little things reminds me

00:33:50.750 --> 00:33:52.590
of my dad sometimes.

00:33:52.590 --> 00:33:54.360
His love of family.

00:33:54.360 --> 00:33:57.290
When he - one of the most
enduring things he ever did

00:33:57.290 --> 00:33:58.810
for me was when we were dating,

00:33:58.810 --> 00:34:00.470
because my mother had
already been widowed,

00:34:00.470 --> 00:34:01.770
he didn't even tell me.

00:34:01.770 --> 00:34:03.440
He sent her a Valentine.

00:34:03.440 --> 00:34:05.250
My brothers are not going
to do anything like that

00:34:05.250 --> 00:34:09.530
for anybody ever, you know,
and my husband does that.

00:34:09.530 --> 00:34:14.470
So, personal relationships
should be respected as such

00:34:14.470 --> 00:34:17.640
and I think interfaith
marriages are happening more

00:34:17.640 --> 00:34:22.050
and more slowly as - as
families become more integrated

00:34:22.050 --> 00:34:23.960
in the United States.

00:34:23.960 --> 00:34:26.370
I think my age group had
the hardest, but when I look

00:34:26.370 --> 00:34:27.800
at people in their 20s,

00:34:27.800 --> 00:34:29.930
I'm amazed they're
dating in college.

00:34:29.930 --> 00:34:31.630
We were not allowed
to date in college.

00:34:31.630 --> 00:34:34.170
I mean, you wouldn't do that.

00:34:34.170 --> 00:34:36.310
People are meeting their
spouses on their own.

00:34:36.310 --> 00:34:39.650
Arranged marriages are
more becoming from my ex -

00:34:39.650 --> 00:34:43.990
from what I've seen more in
name rather than practice.

00:34:43.990 --> 00:34:46.140
You know, I call it
the mommy network.

00:34:46.140 --> 00:34:48.130
You know, parents are
introducing their kids,

00:34:48.130 --> 00:34:49.830
but it's not like,
you know, here's Bob,

00:34:49.830 --> 00:34:51.130
you're marrying him on Friday.

00:34:51.130 --> 00:34:52.430
That's a real arranged marriage.

00:34:52.430 --> 00:34:53.730
That's not happening.

00:34:53.730 --> 00:34:56.420
And, then, you know, in that
same vain, people are looking

00:34:56.420 --> 00:34:58.230
for people who they
get along with

00:34:58.230 --> 00:35:01.500
and that is increasingly
crossing labels,

00:35:01.500 --> 00:35:03.060
whether it's religion
or nationality

00:35:03.060 --> 00:35:06.840
and I think that's just again
part of the immigrant experience

00:35:06.840 --> 00:35:08.910
and not necessarily
unique to Muslims.

00:35:08.910 --> 00:35:10.980
&gt;&gt; That was a great
question and answer.

00:35:10.980 --> 00:35:12.320
We have another one.

00:35:12.320 --> 00:35:17.270
&gt;&gt; So, actually wanted to
join this conversation.

00:35:17.270 --> 00:35:19.130
My father is from Multan.

00:35:19.130 --> 00:35:23.650
He grew up in Delhi, which tells
all the Pakistanis in the room

00:35:23.650 --> 00:35:25.840
that my family isn't Muslim.

00:35:25.840 --> 00:35:30.260
He was born in 1940 and he
came to the United States

00:35:30.260 --> 00:35:31.910
in the early 70s where he met

00:35:31.910 --> 00:35:35.340
and married my white
unitarian mother.

00:35:35.340 --> 00:35:38.810
They got married
in 1973, I think,

00:35:38.810 --> 00:35:41.490
and I think that you're
really right when you say

00:35:41.490 --> 00:35:45.780
that it's different
generationally, right.

00:35:45.780 --> 00:35:47.260
So, I'm about your age

00:35:47.260 --> 00:35:51.030
and I think it's probably very
different for people dating now,

00:35:51.030 --> 00:35:55.570
but for my parents, even then
there were certainly people

00:35:55.570 --> 00:35:58.780
who made my mother welcome
immediately in the community

00:35:58.780 --> 00:36:00.140
and people in my
mother's community

00:36:00.140 --> 00:36:01.850
who made my father welcome.

00:36:01.850 --> 00:36:03.780
I think the issue a
lot of it had to do

00:36:03.780 --> 00:36:06.510
with what were expectations
for children.

00:36:06.510 --> 00:36:11.660
And so, the - I think now
people who are raising kids,

00:36:11.660 --> 00:36:13.790
there's much more acceptance
on the part of the parents

00:36:13.790 --> 00:36:17.720
and the goal is that fluidity,
whereas I think that growing

00:36:17.720 --> 00:36:21.350
up the child in one of those -

00:36:21.350 --> 00:36:24.680
those blended marriages
in the 1980s.

00:36:24.680 --> 00:36:29.440
My sister and I and our
inability to speak Punjabi

00:36:29.440 --> 00:36:32.530
for instance was
scary to parents

00:36:32.530 --> 00:36:34.810
who were immigrant
parents in a way

00:36:34.810 --> 00:36:37.130
that I suspect it's
maybe sad sometimes --

00:36:37.130 --> 00:36:38.440
&gt;&gt; Yeah. Losing identity.

00:36:38.440 --> 00:36:41.650
&gt;&gt; -- for parents now, but it's
not terrifying in the same way.

00:36:41.650 --> 00:36:45.970
And so, I do think it's the sort
of forward moving progression,

00:36:45.970 --> 00:36:48.260
maybe towards something good,
maybe just different, right.

00:36:48.260 --> 00:36:49.850
&gt;&gt; Right.

00:36:49.850 --> 00:36:51.430
&gt;&gt; But, yeah very much
what you're saying

00:36:51.430 --> 00:36:54.120
and I think I see something very
different for friends of mine

00:36:54.120 --> 00:36:56.840
who marry across than
I saw for my parents,

00:36:56.840 --> 00:36:58.190
even though I would
say they found a lot

00:36:58.190 --> 00:37:00.260
of acceptance 50 years ago.

00:37:00.260 --> 00:37:03.240
&gt;&gt; And, I think it'll
be very empowering

00:37:03.240 --> 00:37:06.890
for Muslim communities,
you know, speaking broadly

00:37:06.890 --> 00:37:09.580
because when you
look at Americans

00:37:09.580 --> 00:37:12.570
of Muslim backgrounds
growing up here -

00:37:12.570 --> 00:37:13.870
or even traditional
backgrounds -

00:37:13.870 --> 00:37:15.170
I should probably
take a step back.

00:37:15.170 --> 00:37:16.470
It's not just Muslims.

00:37:16.470 --> 00:37:18.320
A lot of issues that come up in
the Muslim context actually have

00:37:18.320 --> 00:37:20.790
to do with traditional
[inaudible] cultures,

00:37:20.790 --> 00:37:23.190
Middle Eastern cultures, not,
you know, strictly Muslim,

00:37:23.190 --> 00:37:25.170
or Indian cultures,
South Asian culture.

00:37:25.170 --> 00:37:26.470
There's a lot of stuff
especially having to do

00:37:26.470 --> 00:37:28.020
with women's rights issues.

00:37:28.020 --> 00:37:31.350
Anyway. With that, the
point what I was trying -

00:37:31.350 --> 00:37:35.920
my point is more that like
when people like my age group

00:37:35.920 --> 00:37:40.770
or younger grow up in western
cultures like American culture

00:37:40.770 --> 00:37:44.920
and we integrate our
heritage with being American,

00:37:44.920 --> 00:37:46.550
which also includes
American values

00:37:46.550 --> 00:37:49.550
and American sensibilities,
what I'm seeing when you look

00:37:49.550 --> 00:37:52.410
across the media is you also -
you see more liberal interp -

00:37:52.410 --> 00:37:55.540
understandings of what it
means to be a woman or Muslim

00:37:55.540 --> 00:37:59.250
or Pakistani and I think that
goes back into the community.

00:37:59.250 --> 00:38:02.990
So, you know, a little girl
being raised going to Mosques,

00:38:02.990 --> 00:38:04.870
excuse me, today
is probably going

00:38:04.870 --> 00:38:08.940
to hear a lot more enlightened
interpretation of what it means

00:38:08.940 --> 00:38:11.050
to be Muslin or Pakistani
or whatever other, you know,

00:38:11.050 --> 00:38:12.380
national background she might be

00:38:12.380 --> 00:38:16.190
of than maybe what my
mother was exposed to

00:38:16.190 --> 00:38:17.610
or even what I was
exposed to coming

00:38:17.610 --> 00:38:19.660
to America, you know, 1981.

00:38:19.660 --> 00:38:22.400
&gt;&gt; I think for anybody
in this room also

00:38:22.400 --> 00:38:25.530
that has a very compelling
story I do encourage you to go

00:38:25.530 --> 00:38:28.890
on the site and definitely
share your story,

00:38:28.890 --> 00:38:31.260
because it is an open platform.

00:38:31.260 --> 00:38:34.850
You can submit your story, your
headshot and it would be amazing

00:38:34.850 --> 00:38:38.640
to feature you, especially
your unique narrative as well.

00:38:38.640 --> 00:38:44.100
Are there any other questions
from anyplace that I overlooked?

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:46.110
Oh, I'm sorry.

00:38:46.110 --> 00:38:47.410
There you go.

00:38:47.410 --> 00:38:49.620
&gt;&gt; Hi. I had a question
for the last speaker.

00:38:49.620 --> 00:38:56.370
So, I'm kind of wondering what
you - what exactly do you mean

00:38:56.370 --> 00:38:58.590
by the American dream?

00:38:58.590 --> 00:39:01.480
Because like - I don't
know, like it seems

00:39:01.480 --> 00:39:06.110
like the way you're describing
it is kind of like in terms

00:39:06.110 --> 00:39:09.020
of like material successes.

00:39:09.020 --> 00:39:12.280
How do you think that
that kind of intersects

00:39:12.280 --> 00:39:16.960
with the way Muslims in this
country have been criminalized

00:39:16.960 --> 00:39:21.410
and marginalized consistently
and perhaps especially

00:39:21.410 --> 00:39:23.410
under this administration?

00:39:23.410 --> 00:39:25.550
&gt;&gt; Well, I'll - I'll -
I'll start with that.

00:39:25.550 --> 00:39:29.980
I think the most important thing
is that, you know, a) it's the -

00:39:29.980 --> 00:39:33.960
the stories themselves are
not just about material gain,

00:39:33.960 --> 00:39:37.070
but it's about the sacrifices
and the opportunities

00:39:37.070 --> 00:39:40.370
that America has had
provided for people that come

00:39:40.370 --> 00:39:44.010
from all walks of life, you
know, not just Pakistan, but,

00:39:44.010 --> 00:39:45.790
you know, all different
countries

00:39:45.790 --> 00:39:48.760
and not just economic
growth, but actual freedom

00:39:48.760 --> 00:39:51.220
and opportunities and democracy.

00:39:51.220 --> 00:39:54.190
And, you know, there's a lot of
Muslims that come from countries

00:39:54.190 --> 00:39:56.730
where there was a lot of
injustices that also existed

00:39:56.730 --> 00:39:59.500
where democracy doesn't exist.

00:39:59.500 --> 00:40:02.260
I think that's kind of where
Ahmed was touching on that.

00:40:02.260 --> 00:40:05.650
Now, in regards to
anything about politics

00:40:05.650 --> 00:40:06.950
or the current administration,

00:40:06.950 --> 00:40:10.390
that's not something
that we comment on.

00:40:10.390 --> 00:40:14.230
Quite frankly, our organization
and our whole project is

00:40:14.230 --> 00:40:17.880
to exemplify what Muslim
American experiences are

00:40:17.880 --> 00:40:20.720
and how Muslims have contributed

00:40:20.720 --> 00:40:23.440
to this American
fabric of society.

00:40:23.440 --> 00:40:25.880
So, going back into that
Ahmed, you can answer

00:40:25.880 --> 00:40:27.180
that question as well.

00:40:27.180 --> 00:40:30.340
&gt;&gt; Well, it restricts just
a bit, so we can always talk

00:40:30.340 --> 00:40:31.720
after in case you need to.

00:40:31.720 --> 00:40:36.780
But, yeah, it's beyond material
benefit and gain in a spec -

00:40:36.780 --> 00:40:38.870
in a respect of the
American dream.

00:40:38.870 --> 00:40:40.700
I think when I'm referring
to the American dream

00:40:40.700 --> 00:40:43.820
in my parent's eyes, it's really
just making sure that, you know,

00:40:43.820 --> 00:40:46.430
they're children had the
