01:25:26.700 --> 01:25:28.000
for the American
Folklife Center,

01:25:28.000 --> 01:25:30.360
so I'm from that third
organization you have been

01:25:30.360 --> 01:25:31.690
hearing about quite a bit.

01:25:31.690 --> 01:25:34.930
And, I'm here to talk
to you about a sort

01:25:34.930 --> 01:25:36.520
of more general approach

01:25:36.520 --> 01:25:39.200
to collecting cultural
documentation.

01:25:39.200 --> 01:25:44.090
So, I think to begin we can say
that the genius of StoryCorps is

01:25:44.090 --> 01:25:47.690
that the - the StoryCorps
principal was

01:25:47.690 --> 01:25:49.640
to facilitate these
kinds of interviews.

01:25:49.640 --> 01:25:52.120
Right. Make them really
easy for people to do.

01:25:52.120 --> 01:25:55.740
And, in so doing, they -
they sort of made a lot

01:25:55.740 --> 01:25:58.030
of those background decisions
that you have to make

01:25:58.030 --> 01:26:00.180
if you're going to do
cultural documentation,

01:26:00.180 --> 01:26:02.840
they made those decisions
for you and put them in place

01:26:02.840 --> 01:26:05.680
so that you could just
go in and do interviews.

01:26:05.680 --> 01:26:08.400
And, the result of this is
is this amazing collection

01:26:08.400 --> 01:26:11.550
of recorded interviews and
- and what comes out of

01:26:11.550 --> 01:26:14.340
that are these wonderful
edited stories that you hear

01:26:14.340 --> 01:26:17.910
on the radio or that you can
see in animations on YouTube.

01:26:17.910 --> 01:26:20.350
They've done some really great
things with them as well.

01:26:20.350 --> 01:26:25.120
The - the only thing about
this approach that can be seen

01:26:25.120 --> 01:26:27.630
as a drawback is the, you
know, we've got a question,

01:26:27.630 --> 01:26:31.410
for example, are you going
to make a film documentary.

01:26:31.410 --> 01:26:33.950
And, you can't do that
with a documentation

01:26:33.950 --> 01:26:36.240
that StoryCorps has
produced exclusively.

01:26:36.240 --> 01:26:40.120
You would have to go in and make
other documentation including

01:26:40.120 --> 01:26:42.230
footage in order to do that.

01:26:42.230 --> 01:26:45.670
And so, taking a step backwards
is what I'm going to do now

01:26:45.670 --> 01:26:48.760
and talk about doing
documentation, but you have

01:26:48.760 --> 01:26:53.310
to decide what the model is
before you start that process.

01:26:53.310 --> 01:26:56.640
And, I'm going to be talking
sort of jumping off from a book

01:26:56.640 --> 01:26:59.110
that the American Folklife
Center has just put

01:26:59.110 --> 01:27:00.410
out about a year ago.

01:27:00.410 --> 01:27:02.290
It's called Folklife
and Field Work.

01:27:02.290 --> 01:27:04.440
And, there are copies of this
book on the table outside.

01:27:04.440 --> 01:27:06.380
Everyone could have
taken one on the way in,

01:27:06.380 --> 01:27:07.680
but you can now take
one on the way

01:27:07.680 --> 01:27:09.760
out if you didn't take
one on the way in.

01:27:09.760 --> 01:27:14.830
And, this describes that process
of doing cultural documentation

01:27:14.830 --> 01:27:17.890
from the sort of
beginning to the end,

01:27:17.890 --> 01:27:19.190
the soup to nuts approach.

01:27:19.190 --> 01:27:21.710
So, I'm going to start.

01:27:21.710 --> 01:27:23.570
So, this is really
about thinking

01:27:23.570 --> 01:27:29.190
about folklife field work
in - in a digital world.

01:27:29.190 --> 01:27:32.990
So, it begins with this
question of what is folklife

01:27:32.990 --> 01:27:34.290
and here's where I'm nervous.

01:27:34.290 --> 01:27:36.260
You won't be able to read the
slide, but it won't matter,

01:27:36.260 --> 01:27:38.180
because I'll - I'll
read it for you as well.

01:27:38.180 --> 01:27:40.390
So, one of the great
things about being

01:27:40.390 --> 01:27:42.980
at the American Folklife
Center, our - our director

01:27:42.980 --> 01:27:44.780
at the beginning,
Betsy Peterson,

01:27:44.780 --> 01:27:47.300
explained that we were placed
here at The Library of Congress

01:27:47.300 --> 01:27:50.660
in order to document the
diversity of American folklife

01:27:50.660 --> 01:27:53.000
and that really is our
legislation and it's -

01:27:53.000 --> 01:27:56.300
it's an inspiring piece of
legislation because it begins

01:27:56.300 --> 01:28:00.390
by saying how important
diversity is to American life

01:28:00.390 --> 01:28:02.260
and that we should be
documenting it and -

01:28:02.260 --> 01:28:05.340
and keeping - preserving
that documentation

01:28:05.340 --> 01:28:06.760
in The Library of Congress.

01:28:06.760 --> 01:28:09.270
And, so that's - that's a
great part of the legislation,

01:28:09.270 --> 01:28:12.860
but another part is that it
actually defines folklife

01:28:12.860 --> 01:28:15.590
so that it can direct
us as to what it is

01:28:15.590 --> 01:28:17.110
that we're supposed to document.

01:28:17.110 --> 01:28:19.110
And so, this actually
- this definition

01:28:19.110 --> 01:28:22.410
of folklife actually
comes from the public law

01:28:22.410 --> 01:28:24.140
that established the
American Folklife Center,

01:28:24.140 --> 01:28:26.850
so this is the wisdom
of the U.S. Congress.

01:28:26.850 --> 01:28:30.310
And, I'm not just saying
that because I have to.

01:28:30.310 --> 01:28:32.390
So, this is how they
define folklife.

01:28:32.390 --> 01:28:35.850
The traditional expressive
shared culture of various groups

01:28:35.850 --> 01:28:39.790
in the United States,
familial, ethnic, occupational,

01:28:39.790 --> 01:28:41.590
religious and regional.

01:28:41.590 --> 01:28:43.960
It says expressive culture
includes a wide range

01:28:43.960 --> 01:28:47.530
of creative and symbolic
forms such as custom, belief,

01:28:47.530 --> 01:28:51.840
technical skill, language,
literature, art, architecture,

01:28:51.840 --> 01:28:56.100
music, play, dance,
drama, ritual, pageantry

01:28:56.100 --> 01:28:58.350
and handy craft and
that it explains

01:28:58.350 --> 01:29:01.170
that these expressions
are mainly learned orally

01:29:01.170 --> 01:29:04.730
by imitation or in performance
and are generally maintained

01:29:04.730 --> 01:29:07.990
or perpetuated without
benefit or formal instruction

01:29:07.990 --> 01:29:09.590
or institutional direction.

01:29:09.590 --> 01:29:15.180
So, essentially, it's saying
that - that folklife is -

01:29:15.180 --> 01:29:17.490
is sort of small scaled,
traditional culture

01:29:17.490 --> 01:29:21.240
that is maintained in
communities of all kinds.

01:29:21.240 --> 01:29:24.690
And, the American Folklife
Center exists to document

01:29:24.690 --> 01:29:27.450
and preserve such culture.

01:29:27.450 --> 01:29:31.650
So, now the question is
what is this word fieldwork,

01:29:31.650 --> 01:29:34.700
which is in the title, and I
put ethnographic in parentheses

01:29:34.700 --> 01:29:37.320
because other disciplines
use fieldwork too,

01:29:37.320 --> 01:29:40.300
like geologists consider
going out and collecting rocks

01:29:40.300 --> 01:29:41.730
to be a form of fieldwork

01:29:41.730 --> 01:29:43.030
and that's not what
we're talking about.

01:29:43.030 --> 01:29:44.970
We're talking about
cultural documentation.

01:29:44.970 --> 01:29:50.000
So, what fieldwork really is
is the firsthand observation

01:29:50.000 --> 01:29:53.480
and documentation of
culture and this results

01:29:53.480 --> 01:29:55.470
in various forms
of documentation.

01:29:55.470 --> 01:29:58.510
And, you see a list of the kinds
of things that you might end

01:29:58.510 --> 01:30:01.240
up with if you did
ethnographic field work.

01:30:01.240 --> 01:30:04.970
And, many of these forms now are
going to be - come in the form

01:30:04.970 --> 01:30:06.270
of digital files, right.

01:30:06.270 --> 01:30:07.960
Even though they're written
notes, they're actually going

01:30:07.960 --> 01:30:11.340
to be Word documents as opposed
to a notebook in a lot of cases.

01:30:11.340 --> 01:30:14.540
So, you end up with a lot of
digital files and you also end

01:30:14.540 --> 01:30:18.710
up probably with some analog
materials, drawings, objects,

01:30:18.710 --> 01:30:20.750
and I put forms in there,
because it's important

01:30:20.750 --> 01:30:22.050
to get people's permission,

01:30:22.050 --> 01:30:23.350
which we'll talk
about in a minute.

01:30:23.350 --> 01:30:24.650
And, so we - forms come

01:30:24.650 --> 01:30:27.750
with pretty much any
collection of this type.

01:30:27.750 --> 01:30:32.320
And so, here's how you would
get started in such a process.

01:30:32.320 --> 01:30:34.270
The first thing that
you have to do is think

01:30:34.270 --> 01:30:36.720
about what your goals
and outcomes are, right.

01:30:36.720 --> 01:30:39.880
So, one kind of -
of documentation

01:30:39.880 --> 01:30:41.350
or of field work is just

01:30:41.350 --> 01:30:43.360
to understand the
community for yourself.

01:30:43.360 --> 01:30:45.860
So, you're a scholar, right,
and you want to know more

01:30:45.860 --> 01:30:47.630
about this community,
so you go in to -

01:30:47.630 --> 01:30:50.200
to make that understanding
for yourself.

01:30:50.200 --> 01:30:52.480
But, another kind is when
you're helping the community

01:30:52.480 --> 01:30:55.950
in some way, that is they need
to get a grant for example

01:30:55.950 --> 01:30:58.220
and they need documentation
of certain of the things

01:30:58.220 --> 01:31:00.570
that they do in order
to get that grant.

01:31:00.570 --> 01:31:02.630
So, that's another
possible model of -

01:31:02.630 --> 01:31:03.930
of folklife field work.

01:31:03.930 --> 01:31:06.500
It's for helping the community
and the two, of course,

01:31:06.500 --> 01:31:08.330
are not only not
mutually exclusive,

01:31:08.330 --> 01:31:09.980
but they work together
very well.

01:31:09.980 --> 01:31:13.660
So, sometimes you start out
just learning about the culture,

01:31:13.660 --> 01:31:15.660
but then people within
the culture realize

01:31:15.660 --> 01:31:17.640
that there's some way
that you can help them

01:31:17.640 --> 01:31:19.220
with this documentation.

01:31:19.220 --> 01:31:22.180
That happens to folklores all
the time and we role with that.

01:31:22.180 --> 01:31:25.580
We try to help the
communities as much as we can.

01:31:25.580 --> 01:31:27.920
And, finally, a third thing that
you need to think about in terms

01:31:27.920 --> 01:31:31.850
of goals and outcomes is
specific end products.

01:31:31.850 --> 01:31:34.730
Are you, for example,
thinking about writing a book

01:31:34.730 --> 01:31:37.940
or are you going to
make a documentary as -

01:31:37.940 --> 01:31:39.240
as someone mentioned
in the room.

01:31:39.240 --> 01:31:42.430
All of these things - all
of these three decisions -

01:31:42.430 --> 01:31:43.800
are you understanding
the community,

01:31:43.800 --> 01:31:45.530
how are you helping
the community,

01:31:45.530 --> 01:31:47.380
and what specific end
product do you want

01:31:47.380 --> 01:31:50.900
to create will affect the
kinds of docu - documentation

01:31:50.900 --> 01:31:52.200
that you produce, right.

01:31:52.200 --> 01:31:54.890
So, if you - if you know
that you want to make a film,

01:31:54.890 --> 01:31:58.700
then you have to start thinking
about that kind of documentation

01:31:58.700 --> 01:32:02.120
about making video
footage, for example.

01:32:02.120 --> 01:32:05.280
And, then you decide
what to document.

01:32:05.280 --> 01:32:07.180
And, I love the fact that
both Julia and I have the who,

01:32:07.180 --> 01:32:09.220
what, where slide, right.

01:32:09.220 --> 01:32:11.980
But, this is very important
because if you start

01:32:11.980 --> 01:32:13.480
with something that's too broad,

01:32:13.480 --> 01:32:15.630
you will never finish
your project

01:32:15.630 --> 01:32:16.960
or even get your
project started.

01:32:16.960 --> 01:32:21.190
So, you - so really those three
are the three main questions

01:32:21.190 --> 01:32:22.490
that you usually ask.

01:32:22.490 --> 01:32:24.780
Who meaning which community
are you documenting?

01:32:24.780 --> 01:32:28.880
What meaning what facet of this
huge thing called folklife do

01:32:28.880 --> 01:32:31.200
you want to study?

01:32:31.200 --> 01:32:33.750
And, thirdly, where
are you going to do it?

01:32:33.750 --> 01:32:36.550
So, I mean, just as an
example, if you wanted

01:32:36.550 --> 01:32:41.360
to study traditional
Pakistani weddings, right.

01:32:41.360 --> 01:32:44.170
You could - you could say
well, I'll study them all

01:32:44.170 --> 01:32:47.520
over the world, but that would
not be a realistic project.

01:32:47.520 --> 01:32:51.500
So, you want to have, you know,
each one of these items, you -

01:32:51.500 --> 01:32:55.190
you want to have an idea for -
for what the value of that is.

01:32:55.190 --> 01:32:57.370
So, I'm going to do it in
New York City, for example,

01:32:57.370 --> 01:33:01.780
and that will make that project
a lot easier to complete.

01:33:01.780 --> 01:33:05.990
And, then you want to think
in advance about archiving,

01:33:05.990 --> 01:33:08.210
sustainability and
access, right.

01:33:08.210 --> 01:33:10.110
So, you are going
to create files,

01:33:10.110 --> 01:33:13.910
these - these digital files.

01:33:13.910 --> 01:33:16.250
In 20 years, is anyone
going to - going to be able

01:33:16.250 --> 01:33:18.730
to use the files
that you've created?

01:33:18.730 --> 01:33:23.310
That's a problem for all
of us and it's a problem

01:33:23.310 --> 01:33:26.760
that is best solved by
consulting with professionals,

01:33:26.760 --> 01:33:30.710
because it, you know, these
things change all the time

01:33:30.710 --> 01:33:33.290
and folks within archives
and libraries are the people

01:33:33.290 --> 01:33:35.490
who really know the
answers to these questions

01:33:35.490 --> 01:33:39.360
or at least know, you know,
the trajectories that we're on

01:33:39.360 --> 01:33:42.980
and can give you the best
answers that we know today.

01:33:42.980 --> 01:33:45.160
And so, really what
this is saying is

01:33:45.160 --> 01:33:49.450
if you want your collection
to be accessible in the future

01:33:49.450 --> 01:33:51.220
and you want the files
to be sustainable

01:33:51.220 --> 01:33:54.800
so that even you can use them
in the future, you probably want

01:33:54.800 --> 01:33:57.930
to talk to someone at some point
in your process and early -

01:33:57.930 --> 01:33:59.390
the earlier the better, right.

01:33:59.390 --> 01:34:02.660
So, if you talk to an
archivist before you even start,

01:34:02.660 --> 01:34:06.170
that's probably better than
creating the documentation

01:34:06.170 --> 01:34:08.040
and then talking to them later.

01:34:08.040 --> 01:34:10.950
And, what this means is when
you're going to do a project,

01:34:10.950 --> 01:34:13.690
you sort of think about
in advance what kind

01:34:13.690 --> 01:34:18.170
of archive do I think this
might belong in, find that kind

01:34:18.170 --> 01:34:20.470
of archive and talk
to someone there.

01:34:20.470 --> 01:34:23.060
And, even if they aren't
sure they're interested

01:34:23.060 --> 01:34:24.600
in the collection
until they see it,

01:34:24.600 --> 01:34:28.470
which is quite often the case,
they'd be willing often to talk

01:34:28.470 --> 01:34:32.060
to you about what
standards they would accept

01:34:32.060 --> 01:34:33.920
and why they would
accept those standards

01:34:33.920 --> 01:34:36.140
and what your next best
option is and all kinds

01:34:36.140 --> 01:34:37.440
of questions like that.

01:34:37.440 --> 01:34:40.480
So, we really encourage
you to talk to an archive

01:34:40.480 --> 01:34:44.210
in advance of doing a project.

01:34:44.210 --> 01:34:46.770
There are ethics
considerations involved

01:34:46.770 --> 01:34:49.290
in any field work project.

01:34:49.290 --> 01:34:51.890
Mainly, the main
issue is to be honest

01:34:51.890 --> 01:34:53.450
and transparent about
everything.

01:34:53.450 --> 01:34:55.130
So, never deceive people.

01:34:55.130 --> 01:34:58.360
Never collect information
on false pretenses.

01:34:58.360 --> 01:35:00.930
If you don't know what
you're going to do

01:35:00.930 --> 01:35:04.170
with the documentation, it's -
that's okay, but if you do know,

01:35:04.170 --> 01:35:06.980
if you know you're making a
film, then you should tell them

01:35:06.980 --> 01:35:08.590
that that's what you're doing.

01:35:08.590 --> 01:35:10.910
There's - there's really
not a good reason usually

01:35:10.910 --> 01:35:14.010
to conceal what you're
doing from the people

01:35:14.010 --> 01:35:15.630
that you're interviewing.

01:35:15.630 --> 01:35:17.970
And, the second part
of this is to make sure

01:35:17.970 --> 01:35:20.230
that you get permission,
express permission,

01:35:20.230 --> 01:35:24.050
to use people's materials, that
is their image, their voice.

01:35:24.050 --> 01:35:26.800
And, usually we do this through
the use of release forms,

01:35:26.800 --> 01:35:31.720
which I'll talk about a little
bit in a - in a few minutes.

01:35:31.720 --> 01:35:35.330
After you've done all that,
right, after you know what kind

01:35:35.330 --> 01:35:37.720
of project you're doing,
where you're doing it,

01:35:37.720 --> 01:35:41.480
what kind of archive you might
want to turn this material into,

01:35:41.480 --> 01:35:44.010
what kind of standards
that archive would need,

01:35:44.010 --> 01:35:46.070
all of those questions,
then you can decide

01:35:46.070 --> 01:35:47.880
on the equipment needs

01:35:47.880 --> 01:35:51.040
for recording this
particular project.

01:35:52.100 --> 01:35:55.560
After you do that, you do
some preliminary research,

01:35:55.560 --> 01:35:59.310
that is to say you're studying
Pakistani weddings in New York,

01:35:59.310 --> 01:36:02.120
well you go online and see what
you can find out about that.

01:36:02.120 --> 01:36:04.700
You go to the library and you
see if there are books about it,

01:36:04.700 --> 01:36:09.950
articles about it that can help
you in your - in your planning

01:36:09.950 --> 01:36:12.020
of the initial kinds
of fieldwork.

01:36:12.020 --> 01:36:13.890
And, then you start making
community connections.

01:36:13.890 --> 01:36:17.270
Now, in many cases, people
who are starting this kind

01:36:17.270 --> 01:36:18.820
of project are starting it

01:36:18.820 --> 01:36:20.590
because they already have
community connections.

01:36:20.590 --> 01:36:22.390
They know someone in
the community, they -

01:36:22.390 --> 01:36:24.890
they've been interested
in it for a long time,

01:36:24.890 --> 01:36:27.910
but if you don't, you
look for cultural centers.

01:36:27.910 --> 01:36:29.870
You look for civic
organizations.

01:36:29.870 --> 01:36:33.270
Those kinds of places that
are used to being brokers

01:36:33.270 --> 01:36:36.920
between the culture and other
people who are from outside.

01:36:36.920 --> 01:36:39.070
And, you go and talk to them
and see whom might be interested

01:36:39.070 --> 01:36:41.890
in talking to you, what
use this project might have

01:36:41.890 --> 01:36:44.620
within the community and
how you can help and fit

01:36:44.620 --> 01:36:47.100
into the community's needs.

01:36:47.100 --> 01:36:50.120
And, after you do that,
you can then decide

01:36:50.120 --> 01:36:52.450
on the real specifics of
what you want to document.

01:36:52.450 --> 01:36:56.150
So, you know, I've got
to now come up with a way

01:36:56.150 --> 01:37:01.750
to document the dress,
the music, and the food

01:37:01.750 --> 01:37:03.880
that are going to be part

01:37:03.880 --> 01:37:06.140
of three Pakistani
weddings in New York.

01:37:06.140 --> 01:37:08.960
This is just a project that
I made up for the purposes

01:37:08.960 --> 01:37:11.760
of this talk, but that's an
example of the kinds of things

01:37:11.760 --> 01:37:14.150
that you - that you then come
up with when you narrow it

01:37:14.150 --> 01:37:18.190
down to - to this
level of the specifics.

01:37:18.190 --> 01:37:21.790
And, you then start
thinking about this process

01:37:21.790 --> 01:37:25.680
that in anthropology or folklore
we call participant observation.

01:37:25.680 --> 01:37:29.510
Okay. So, how is it that you are
going to be part of these events

01:37:29.510 --> 01:37:33.740
and not be in the way and
there are two ways to do that,

01:37:33.740 --> 01:37:37.160
usually that - that - that
ethnographers use a lot.

01:37:37.160 --> 01:37:39.200
One is to become a
learner of some kind.

01:37:39.200 --> 01:37:41.700
So, if you're interested in a
musical tradition, for example,

01:37:41.700 --> 01:37:44.450
you apprentice yourself
to a player and you learn

01:37:44.450 --> 01:37:46.570
to play the instrument
and you document it

01:37:46.570 --> 01:37:48.710
through that process
of learning.

01:37:48.710 --> 01:37:50.730
And, the other is to become
a helper of some kind.

01:37:50.730 --> 01:37:53.280
So, if you're - if you're
not going to be the chef

01:37:53.280 --> 01:37:56.370
at the wedding, you can
still help sweep the floor

01:37:56.370 --> 01:37:59.470
and do other unglamorous
but very useful tasks

01:37:59.470 --> 01:38:03.030
that will put you in the place
that you want to be in order

01:38:03.030 --> 01:38:05.670
to document it and make
you useful to the community

01:38:05.670 --> 01:38:08.330
so that they're happier
there and they're happy

01:38:08.330 --> 01:38:11.790
that you're documenting
their event as well.

01:38:11.790 --> 01:38:15.610
And, then once you've - you've
got yourself, you know, you -

01:38:15.610 --> 01:38:18.230
you - you got yourself
placed, that's when you figure

01:38:18.230 --> 01:38:20.940
out who the people are that
you're going to interview

01:38:20.940 --> 01:38:25.710
and you're going to setup
your first interviews.

01:38:25.710 --> 01:38:28.220
And, then, of course, before
you actually go in the field,

01:38:28.220 --> 01:38:30.690
you have to learn to use that
equipment that you selected

01:38:30.690 --> 01:38:32.010
through that other process,

01:38:32.010 --> 01:38:34.520
which just means you have a
little practice, you know,

01:38:34.520 --> 01:38:37.640
have some practice sessions
and go through that.

01:38:37.640 --> 01:38:40.440
And, I mentioned release forms.

01:38:40.440 --> 01:38:43.630
You want to design release forms
or obtain them from somewhere.

01:38:43.630 --> 01:38:45.570
This book has release
forms in it,

01:38:45.570 --> 01:38:48.550
so that's a very helpful
thing that you can just pull

01:38:48.550 --> 01:38:50.980
out the versions
that are in here.

01:38:50.980 --> 01:38:53.880
And, those release forms are
again to give you permission

01:38:53.880 --> 01:38:55.760
to use what you collect.

01:38:55.760 --> 01:38:59.470
So, if I have done an interview
with someone on video and I want

01:38:59.470 --> 01:39:02.310
to put it in a film, it's
helpful from the beginning

01:39:02.310 --> 01:39:03.840
to have had that
person's consent,

01:39:03.840 --> 01:39:05.850
because otherwise you
might go back to them later

01:39:05.850 --> 01:39:08.180
and they say well, you know,
I was happy to talk to you,

01:39:08.180 --> 01:39:11.300
but I don't want it in the
film and then, you know, that -

01:39:11.300 --> 01:39:13.800
that amount of footage is
not as - as helpful to you

01:39:13.800 --> 01:39:15.100
as it would have been.

01:39:15.100 --> 01:39:17.030
So, it's always good to
know these things in advance

01:39:17.030 --> 01:39:20.460
and this is why you have your
release forms at the outset.

01:39:20.460 --> 01:39:26.260
And, then you can go ahead
and schedule your interviews.

01:39:26.260 --> 01:39:28.590
You create your questions,
so you, you know,

01:39:28.590 --> 01:39:31.160
you figure out what it is you
want to ask and how you're going

01:39:31.160 --> 01:39:33.920
to get the information that
you need and you go ahead

01:39:33.920 --> 01:39:35.840
and you conduct your
first interview.

01:39:35.840 --> 01:39:38.460
So, now my point in going
through all those steps was

01:39:38.460 --> 01:39:40.360
to show you that
with StoryCorps,

01:39:40.360 --> 01:39:42.210
the wonderful thing is
you walk into the booth

01:39:42.210 --> 01:39:44.180
and you conduct your
first interview.

01:39:44.180 --> 01:39:47.830
You don't have to go
through those - those steps.

01:39:47.830 --> 01:39:50.970
But, if you're doing a different
kind of documentary project,

01:39:50.970 --> 01:39:53.660
you do and it's a really
good idea to have all

01:39:53.660 --> 01:39:56.280
of this stuff thought
out in advance

01:39:56.280 --> 01:39:58.190
and this is what the process

01:39:58.190 --> 01:40:00.040
of folklife fieldwork
often is like.

01:40:00.040 --> 01:40:01.340
So, that's just the beginning.

01:40:01.340 --> 01:40:03.530
So, then you've just gotten
your first interview and then,

01:40:03.530 --> 01:40:06.460
of course, from there, you
just take it from there, right.

01:40:06.460 --> 01:40:08.820
Those people will introduce
you to other people,

01:40:08.820 --> 01:40:10.400
you know what the events
are, you've thought

01:40:10.400 --> 01:40:12.320
about what the events are
that you have to document

01:40:12.320 --> 01:40:16.200
and how you have to do that, so
you then you have a plan for -

01:40:16.200 --> 01:40:19.300
for the process of this project.

01:40:19.300 --> 01:40:23.170
So, as you see, there are a lot
of steps involved in planning it

01:40:23.170 --> 01:40:26.190
that - that you don't have to do
at StoryCorps, but if you're -

01:40:26.190 --> 01:40:28.450
if you're starting from
scratch, you might have

01:40:28.450 --> 01:40:30.250
to do all of these things.

01:40:30.250 --> 01:40:31.550
One thing to keep in mind,

01:40:31.550 --> 01:40:34.610
I know that this can sound
daunting, and so the last thing

01:40:34.610 --> 01:40:37.430
to keep in mind is have
fun on your project.

01:40:37.430 --> 01:40:39.910
Don't let it get - don't
let it bog you down.

01:40:39.910 --> 01:40:41.210
And, a lot of the
time, you know,

01:40:41.210 --> 01:40:45.420
you'll find that you get
interested in doing a project

01:40:45.420 --> 01:40:48.190
like this because you
already have relationships

01:40:48.190 --> 01:40:51.180
in the community and sometimes
the community has already

01:40:51.180 --> 01:40:54.220
started the process of
documentation and you are sort

01:40:54.220 --> 01:40:57.210
of contributing to something
that's already ongoing.

01:40:57.210 --> 01:40:58.760
And, if that's the case,

01:40:58.760 --> 01:41:01.750
although you can't
make this plan

01:41:01.750 --> 01:41:04.260
from the very beginning
the way I just outlined,

01:41:04.260 --> 01:41:06.770
you can take a look at
what's already there,

01:41:06.770 --> 01:41:09.810
see how well it fits
into these parameters

01:41:09.810 --> 01:41:13.620
and do anything retro -
retroactively that you can

01:41:13.620 --> 01:41:16.450
to get this ready
for archiving later.

01:41:16.450 --> 01:41:19.450
And, if you - there
are other tips.

01:41:19.450 --> 01:41:22.590
I can't go through the
whole book, but you can,

01:41:22.590 --> 01:41:24.990
because the book is free and
it's right outside on the table.

01:41:24.990 --> 01:41:26.690
So, there are other tips

01:41:26.690 --> 01:41:30.570
for doing a whole
ethnographic project

01:41:30.570 --> 01:41:35.810
and for making those materials
that you create sustainable

01:41:35.810 --> 01:41:39.780
and accessible in the future in
an archive and we really hope

01:41:39.780 --> 01:41:42.390
that you'll do that and you'll
think about all the great ways

01:41:42.390 --> 01:41:44.890
that you can go out there
and - and document culture.

01:41:44.890 --> 01:41:48.060
So, once again I want to
thank all our friends at MALA

01:41:48.060 --> 01:41:51.500
and StoryCorps and on behalf of
the American Folklife Center,

01:41:51.500 --> 01:41:53.510
just say thank you for coming.

